                        <h2 class="section-title">
                            <svg width="28" height="28" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"><path d="M4 19.5v-15A2.5 2.5 0 0 1 6.5 2H20v20H6.5a2.5 2.5 0 0 1-2.5-2.5Z"/><path d="M6 6h10M6 10h10"/></svg>
                            Key Architect Insights
                        </h2>
                        <ul class="bullet-list">
                            <li><strong>The Core of Clean Architecture:</strong> Keeping core business Domain rules completely decoupled from external UI, databases, and third-party framework details.</li>
                            <li><strong>The 1-to-1 Interface Trap:</strong> Creating interfaces for literally every single service (e.g. <code>IUserService</code> for only one <code>UserService</code>) is often unnecessary overhead unless mocked dynamically in unit tests.</li>
                            <li><strong>Vertical Slice Alternative:</strong> Group files by business features (e.g., <code>Features/Orders/CreateOrder.cs</code>) rather than logical layers. Features operate independently and bypass rigid multi-tiered abstraction if overkill.</li>
                            <li><strong>MediatR & REPR:</strong> MediatR is useful for decoupling vertical handler flows, but you can achieve modular architecture safely using direct <em>Request-Endpoint-Response (REPR)</em> structures.</li>
                            <li><strong>The Hybrid Approach:</strong> Combine templates! Use modular monolith boundaries for clean domains, but leverage feature slices internally for optimal speed.</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>

